{
  "text": "The Coronary Artery Risk Development in Young Adults (CARDIA) Study is a multicenter population-based study of CVD risk factor evolution in young adults in 4 US areas-Birmingham, Ala; Chicago, Ill; Minneapolis, Minn; and Oakland, Calif. Stratification was used to obtain nearly equal numbers of blacks and whites, younger (18-24 years) and older (25-30 years) individuals, and those with more (Ͼhigh school) and less (Յhigh school) education. A total of 5111 (51% of eligible participants) attended the baseline examination (year 0) in 1985-1986, with higher participation rates for men, whites, and highly educated individuals. [CITATION_1] The cohort has been followed for 10 years to date, with follow-up examinations at years 2 (1987-1988) , 5 (1990-1991) , 7 (1992-1993) , and 10 (1995-1996) .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "19496186"
